NEWCASTLE DISEASE, POULTRY, OSTRICH - CYPRUS: OIE
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 8 Jan 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE Disease Information, Vol. 19 - No. 1 [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/A_CURRENT.HTM#Sec3>

Newcastle Disease In Cyprus; Isolation of the virus in wildlife
-----------------------------------------------
See also:
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_06.HTM#Sec2> 11 Feb 2005,
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_08.HTM#Sec5> 28 Jan 2005,
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_09.HTM#Sec3> 21 Jan 2005.
Date of previous outbreak of Newcastle disease in Cyprus reported to
the OIE: January 2005
Immediate notification report and final report
Information received on 30 Dec 2005 from Dr. Phedias Loucaides,
Director of Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture, Nicosia:
Report date: 16 Dec 2005
Reason for immediate notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
or infection in a country or zone/compartment following a report
declaring the outbreak(s) ended.
Date of 1st confirmation of the event: 14 Dec 2005
Date of start of the event: 3 Nov 2005
Clinical disease: no
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory
The virus was isolated from a fecal sample taken on 3 Nov 2005 at a
dam located in the eastern part of the island, close to Achna
village. The sample was collected within the framework of the
surveillance program for avian influenza in poultry and wild birds.
Diagnosis: the virus was typed as an avian paramyxovirus 1 (PMV-1).
It was sent afterwards to the OIE Reference Laboratory at Weybridge,
United Kingdom, where it was confirmed as belonging to the PMV-1
subtype. The virus has been placed in lineage 4a and grouped with a
99.7 percent identity with an isolate submitted by Cyprus in 2004.
Laboratories where diagnostic tests were performed: Veterinary
Services Virology Laboratory.
Samples examined: feces
Diagnostic tests used: hemagglutination test
Date: 3 Nov 2005
Results: positive
Laboratories where diagnostic tests were performed: VLA Weybridge,
United Kingdom (OIE Reference Laboratory for avian influenza and
Newcastle disease).
Samples examined: feces
Diagnostic tests used: sequencing at the cleavage site
Date: 14 Dec 2005
Results: positive
Source of outbreak or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive
Control measures:
- control of wildlife reservoirs;
- movement control inside the country;
- vaccination.
Vaccination in response to the outbreak:
Location: All backyard birds in a radius of 3 km and the flocks of
the 2 neighboring commercial farms (one poultry farm and one ostrich
farm) have been vaccinated and booster vaccinated, respectively.
Species: poultry and ostriches
Total number of vaccinated animals: -
Details of the vaccine: inactivated polyvalent vaccine
Treatment of affected animals: no
Final report: yes
